g.title: n2
g.text: Unbroken Sequence of Devon Strata
In Devon, all the strata - older than
the New Red Sandstone - form an
unbroken sequence of strata #ev

g.title: n319
g.text: Unbroken Sequence - Exmoor YDS
If South Devon NC strata are older than
BCL strata and BCL strata are older
than MC strataand MC strata are older
than Exmoor strata, and, in Devon, the
sequence is unbroken, then all
passages between them are conformable
#GRE #pri

g.title: n330
g.text: Unbroken Sequence - MC YDS - 2
If NC strata are older than BCL strata
and BCL strata are older than MC
strata, and in Devon, the sequence is
unbroken, then, all passages between
them are conformable #DEV #pri

g.title: n345
g.text: Unbroken Sequence - South Devon LSTs
YDS - 2
If the main part of NC strata are older
than BCL strata and BCL strata are
older than MC strataand MC strata are
older than some South Devon LSTs, and
in Devon, the sequence is unbroken,
then, all passages between them are
conformable #GRE #pri

g.title: n3
g.text: CM Plants in Devon Culm
Near Bideford (North Devon), there are
CM fossil plants in the main part of
the Culm strata (in close association
with seams of imperfect anthracite) #ev

g.title: n4
g.text: Passing Devon Northwards
Passing Devon from south to north, the
strata become younger, except the
strata north of Exmoor which are of
the same age as the strata south of
Exmoor #ev

g.title: n150
g.text: Exmoor Youngest Devonian Strata
In Devon, the strata of Exmoor are the
youngest #GRE #chron-hyp

g.title: n267
g.text: Trough through Exmoor - GRE.1a
If the existence of a trough running
trough Exmoor is the best explanation
of the Exmoor strata being juxtaposed
solely with older strata, then there
is a trough through Exmoor #GRE

g.title: n268
g.text: Exmoor and South Devon - YDS and ODS
If BCL strata constitute the oldest
part of the Culm series and,
northwards, strata become younger,
except the strata north of Exmoor
which are of the same age as the
strata south of Exmoor,then temporal
order of Devon is as follows: Exmoor,
MC, BCL, South Devon NC #pri #chron-hyp

g.title: n5
g.text: Trough through Exmoor
There is a trough through Exmoor -
formed by a band of limestone running
out to the north coast at Ilfracombe
and south of Barnstaple #ev

g.title: n6
g.text: NC CRT - CAM
Non-Culm strata are of characteristic
CAM rock type #ev

g.title: n55
g.text: CRT - CAM
For the CAM period, there is (at least)
one characteristic rock type #dat-met

g.title: n244
g.text: Non-Culm as CAM - CRTP - Devon - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
non-Culm strata are of characteristic
CAM rock type, then they are CAM in
age #GRE

g.title: n7
g.text: MC CRT - CAM
Main Culm strata are of characteristic
CAM rock type #ev

g.title: n222
g.text: Main Culm as CAM - CRTP - Devon - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
MC strata are of characteristic CAM
rock type, then they are are CAM in
age #GRE

g.title: n8
g.text: BCL CRT - CAM
BCL strata are of characteristic CAM RT
#ev

g.title: n237
g.text: BCL as CAM - CRTP - Devon - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
BCL strata are of characteristic CAM
rock type, then they are CAM in age
#GRE

g.title: n9
g.text: Scottish ORS - Rocks
Scottish ORS strata support a distinct
RT, namely red sandstone #ev

g.title: n199
g.text: Scottland - CRTP - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CRTs and Scottish ORS strata
support red sandstone, then such a RT
is characteristic of the ORS period
#cor

g.title: n205
g.text: Scottish ORS - CRTP - V2 - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CRTs and Scottish ORS strata
support red sandstone, then such a RT
is characteristic of the ORS period
#cor

g.title: n10
g.text: Scottish ORS - Fossils
Scottish ORS strata support only a few
peculiar fish fossils not known from
other strata (e.g Holoptychius),
lacking in any ordinary marine fossils
(such as mollusks, brachiopods and
corals) #ev

g.title: n195
g.text: Scottland - CFP - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFs and Scottish ORS strata
support only peculiar fish fossil
species,then some of these are
characteristic of the ORS period #cor

g.title: n197
g.text: Scottland - CFAP - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and the Scottish ORS strata
support only a few peculiar fish
fossils, then such a FA is
characteristic of the ORS period #cor

g.title: n203
g.text: Scottland - CFAP - V2 - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and the Scottish ORS strata
support only a few peculiar fish
fossils, then such a FA is
characteristic of the ORS period #cor

g.title: n11
g.text: Northwest France
In northwest France, in pre-ORS strata,
associated with seams of coal, there
are some CM fossil plants #ev

g.title: n12
g.text: Carb Fossils in Pre-ORS strata
In pre-ORS strata, there are
Carboniferous fossils #GRE

g.title: n13
g.text: Pembrokeshire - Appearance
Near Pembrokeshire (southwest Wales),
some strata are pre-ORS in appearance
#ev

g.title: n201
g.text: Pembrokeshire - LV in Sedimentation
If some strata are CM in age and
pre-ORS in appearance, then there are
LV in sedimentation during the CM era
#cor

g.title: n14
g.text: LV in Fauna and Flora -Today
Today, there are local variations in
fauna and flora #ev

g.title: n15
g.text: SIL Fossils in North Devon
In north Devon, near Barnstaple, there
are characteristic SIL fossils in the
non-Culm strata #ev

g.title: n16
g.text: Characteristic Fossil - Some Time
For some time intervall dt, there is
(at least) one characteristic fossil
species #dat-met

g.title: n246
g.text: Some Non-Culm as SIL - CFP
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic fossils and the
non-Culm strata around Pilton support
characteristic SIL fossils, then they
are SIL in age #COA

g.title: n17
g.text: Culm trough in Central Devon
In central Devon, there is a Culm
trough - formed by a band of black
limestone outcropping south of
Barnstaple and north of Dartmoor #ev

g.title: n18
g.text: BCL - FA
Most of the fossil species supported by
BCL strata are known from Yorkshire ML
strata #ev

g.title: n240
g.text: BCL as ML - CFAP V2 - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and most of the fossil
species supported by BCL strata are
known from Yorkshire ML strata, then
they are are ML in age #DEV

g.title: n19
g.text: ML and Pennines
All over the Pennines, there is a huge
lateral variation in the ML strata RT
#ev

g.title: n20
g.text: LV in Sedimentation - ML
There are local variations in
sedimentation during the ML period
#dat-met

g.title: n21
g.text: Carboniferous Plants in North Devon
In north Devon, some NC strata support
Carboniferous plant fossils #ev

g.title: n22
g.text: No Carb Fossils in NC Strata
There are no Carboniferous fossils in
NC strata #COA

g.title: n186
g.text: NC as Pre-ORS - Carb Fossils - North
Devon
If, in north Devon, some NC strata
support Carboniferous fossil plants
and there are no such fossils in
pre-ORS strata, then these strata are
at oldest ORS in age #COA

g.title: n23
g.text: No Holoptychius in North Devon
In north Devon, the whole NC strata do
not support peculiar fish fossils like
for example the Holoptychius #ev

g.title: n24
g.text: South Devonian Fossil Fauna
Around Tor Bay and Netwon Abott, the
limestones support not one single SIL
fossil (and no peculiar fish fossil
like for example the Holoptychius),
but many ML shells and a great many
new species #ev

g.title: n190
g.text: NC as Pre-ORS - Carb Fossils - South
Devon
If, in South Devon, some LSTs support
Carboniferous fossils and there are no
such fossils in pre-ORS strata, then
these strata are at oldest ORS in age
#COA

g.title: n25
g.text: Reddish Strata in South Devon
Above the Plymouth limestone but below
the Great Limestone, there is a
distinctive formation of reddish
strata containing everywhere abundance
of fossils (but no peculiar ORS fish
fossils) #ev

g.title: n142
g.text: Between South Devon LSTs - CRT
NC strata above the Plymouth but below
the Great Limestone support red
sandstone #roc-hyp

g.title: n146
g.text: Between South Devonian LSTs - FA - 2
NC strata above the Plymouth but below
the Great Limestone contain everywhere
abundance of fossils (but no peculiar
ORS fish fossils) #fos-hyp

g.title: n26
g.text: MC - FA
Most of the fossil species supported by
MC strata are known from CM strata #ev

g.title: n227
g.text: No Main Culm as CM - CFAP V2 - Devon - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and most of fossil species
supported by MC strata are known from
CM strata, then they are CM in age #GRE

g.title: n27
g.text: Sequence of Strata - Tor Bay and Newton
Abott
Around Tor Bay and Newton Abott, (i)
strata are undisturbed and (ii) some
LSTs overlay MC strata, BCL strata and
the main part of NC strata,
respectively #ev

g.title: n312
g.text: Tor Bay and Newton Abott - TO3 - 1
If (i) originally, the younger
sediments rest on older ones and(ii)
some LSTs overlay MC strata, BCL
strata and the main part of NC strata,
respectively, then, given these strata
are undisturbed, these LSTs are
younger than MC strata, BCL strata and
the main part of the NC strata,
respectively #GRE

g.title: n28
g.text: Non-Culm Fossil Mixture - Devon
In north Devon, the non-Culm fossils
are a mixture of ML shells, USIL
corals, one ORS mollusk and
Carboniferous plants; some trilobites
similar to USIL ones and some totally
new fossils; in south Devon, few
non-Culm fossils are strictly ML
fossils; many fossils are new #ev

g.title: n29
g.text: Philipps' Collection
Most of the fossil species supported by
MC and BCL strata are known from CM
and ML strata, respectively, NC strata
support a FA intermediate in character
between the SIL and ML #ev

g.title: n30
g.text: NC - FA - 2
NC strata support fossils intermediate
in character between SIL and ML
#fos-hyp

g.title: n31
g.text: Valday Hills
In the Valday Hills (Russia), some
strata, sandwiched between undisturbed
SIL and ML strata, supportboth
limestones fossils intermediate in
character between SIL and ML and
sandstones with peculiar ORS fish #ev

g.title: n210
g.text: Russian Strata as ORS - CFAP V2 - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic fossil
assemblages and some strata in the
Valday Hills support fossils
intermediate in character between SIL
and ML as well as peculiar ORS fish,
then they are ORS in age. #DEV

g.title: n212
g.text: Russian Strata as ORS - CRTP V2 - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock types and
some strata in the Valday Hills
support limestones as well as red
sandstone, then they are ORS in age.
#DEV

g.title: n182
g.text: MC as Pre-ORS - Carb Fossils
If the MC strata are pre-ORS in age and
there are no Carboniferous fossils in
pre-ORS strata, then there are no
Carboniferous fossils in MC strata #GRE

g.title: n184
g.text: LP, Pre-ORS and Carb - 2
If there are no Carboniferous fossils
in pre-ORS strata, then Carboniferous
and pre-ORS strata are sufficiently
different in age #COA

g.title: n185
g.text: NC as ORS - Carb Fossils - North Devon
If NC strata are ORS in age and there
are no Carboniferous fossils in ORS
strata, then there are no
Carboniferous fossils in NC strata #GRE

g.title: n70
g.text: Carb and Pre-ORS - Sufficiently
Different
Carboniferous strata and pre-ORS strata
are sufficiently different #COA

g.title: n183
g.text: LP, Pre-ORS and Carb - 1
If Carboniferous and pre-ORS strata are
sufficiently different in age, then
there are no Carboniferous fossils in
pre-ORS strata #COA

g.title: n72
g.text: Some North Devon NC at Oldest ORS
In north Devon, some NC strata
supporting Carboniferous fossils are
at oldest ORS in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n187
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in North Devon - 1
If, in north Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossil
plants, are at oldest ORS in age, and
are not ORS in age, then these strata
are at oldest ML in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n73
g.text: Some North Devon NC at Oldest ML
In north Devon, some NC strata
supporting Carboniferous fossils are
at oldest ML in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n188
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in North Devon - 2
If, in north Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossil
plants, are at oldest ML in age, and
are not ML in age, then these strata
are CM in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n189
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in North Devon - 3
If, in north Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossil
plants, are at oldest ML in age, and
are not CM in age, then these strata
are ML in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n74
g.text: Some ML in North Devon
In north Devon, some NC strata
supporting Carboniferous fossils are
ML in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n76
g.text: Some ORS in North Devon
In north Devon, some NC strata are ORS
in age #DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n75
g.text: Some Non-Culm as ML
Some part of the non-Culm strata is ML
in age #pri #chron-hyp

g.title: n79
g.text: Some Non-Culm as ORS
Some part of the non-Culm strata is ORS
in age #pri #chron-hyp

g.title: n247
g.text: No ORS Non-Culm in North Devon - CFP - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFs and some north Devonian
non-Culm strata are ORS in age, then
they support characteristic ORS fish
fossils #COA

g.title: n250
g.text: ORS in North Devon - CFA ORS V2 - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and some north Devonian NC
strata are ORS in age, then these
strata support few fossils and most of
these are peculiar fish fossils only
known from the ORS #DEV

g.title: n252
g.text: ORS in North Devon - CFA ORS II V2 - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and some north Devonian NC
strata are ORS in age, then these
strata support a FA intermediate in
character between those of SIL and ML
strata #DEV

g.title: n77
g.text: Some CM in North Devon
In north Devon, some NC strata
supporting Carboniferous fossils are
CM in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n78
g.text: Some Non-Culm as CM
Some part of the non-Culm strata is CM
in age #pri #chron-hyp

g.title: n82
g.text: Some South Devon LSTs at Oldest ORS
In South Devon, some LSTs supporting
Carboniferous fossils are at oldest
ORS in age #chron-hyp #COA

g.title: n191
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in South Devon - 1
If, in South Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossils, are
at oldest ORS in age, and are not ORS
in age, then these strata are at
oldest ML in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n83
g.text: Some South Devon LSTs at Oldest ML
In South Devon, some LSTs supporting
Carboniferous fossils are at oldest ML
in age #chron-hyp

g.title: n192
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in South Devon - 2
If, in South Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossils, are
at oldest ML in age, and are not ML in
age, then these strata are CM in age
#chron-hyp

g.title: n193
g.text: Some NC at Oldest ML in South Devon - 3
If, in South Devon, some NC strata,
supporting Carboniferous fossils, are
at oldest ML in age, and are not CM in
age, then these strata are ML in age
#chron-hyp

g.title: n84
g.text: Some South Devon LSTs as ML
In South Devon, some LSTs supporting
Carboniferous fossils are ML in age
#chron-hyp

g.title: n85
g.text: Some South Devon LSTs as ORS
In south Devon, around Tor Bay and
Netwon Abott, the limestones are
(upper) ORS in age #DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n86
g.text: Some South Devon LSTs as CM
In South Devon, some LSTs supporting
Carboniferous fossils are CM in age
#chron-hyp

g.title: n38
g.text: No Characteristic Fossil
For no time intervall dt, there is (at
least) one characteristic fossil
species #dat-met

g.title: n32
g.text: Characteristic Rock Type Principle
There is a bijection between the age of
some strata t and its characteristic
rock types #dat-met

g.title: n58
g.text: Characteristic Rock Type Principle - V2
Given a sufficiently large (i) amount
of rock specimens and (ii) region
under study, for two strata A and B,
it holds: There is a bijection between
the age of some strata and its
characteristic rock types #dat-met

g.title: n173
g.text: CRTP and CRT - 2
Given a certain definition of CRT and
the CRT Principle, it holds: For each
time intervall dt, there is at least
one CRT #dat-met

g.title: n243
g.text: Non-Culm as CAM - CRTP - Devon
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
non-Culm strata are CAM in age, then
they are of characteristic CAM rock
type #GRE

g.title: n221
g.text: Main Culm as CAM - CRTP - Devon
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
MC strata are CAM in age, then they
are of characteristic CAM rock type
#GRE

g.title: n198
g.text: Scottland - CRTP - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CRTs and the RT characteristic
of the ORS period is red sandstone,
then Scottish ORS strata support red
sandstone #cor

g.title: n200
g.text: Pembrokeshire - CRTP
If some strata near Pembrokeshire are
of characteristic CAM rock type, then
they are CAM in age #cor

g.title: n236
g.text: BCL as CAM - CRTP - Devon
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic rock type and the
BCL strata are CAM in age, then they
are of characteristic CAM rock type
#GRE

g.title: n33
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Principle
There is a bijection between the age of
some strata t and its characteristic
fossils #dat-met

g.title: n167
g.text: CFP and CF - 2
Given a certain definition of CF and
the CF Principle, it holds: For each
time intervall dt, there is at least
one CF #dat-met

g.title: n248
g.text: No ORS Non-Culm in North Devon - CFP - 2
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFs and some north Devonian
non-Culm strata support characteristic
ORS fish fossils, then they are ORS in
age #COA

g.title: n224
g.text: Main Culm as CM - CFP
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic fossils and the
MC strata support characteristic CM
fossils, then they are CM in age #COA

g.title: n225
g.text: Main Culm as CM - CFP -2
If strata can be identified by means of
their characteristic fossils and the
MC strata are CM in age, then they
support characteristic CM fossils #COA

g.title: n194
g.text: Scottland - CFP - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFs and fossils characteristic
of the ORS period are some peculiar
fossil fish species, then Scottish ORS
strata support such species #cor

g.title: n34
g.text: Lyellian Principle
For two strata A and B it holds: (i)
The more A and B are similar in their
FSAs, the more they are similar in
age, (ii) the more A and B are similar
in age, the more they are similar in
their FSAs and (iii) if A and B are
sufficiently unsimilar in age, then
they have no species in common #dat-met

g.title: n35
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Assemblage
Principle
There is a bijection between the age of
some strata and its characteristic
fossil assemblages #dat-met

g.title: n56
g.text: Lyellian Principle - V2
Given a sufficiently large (i) amount
of fossils and (ii) region under
study, for two strata A and B, it
holds: (ia) The more A and B are
similar in their FSAs, the more they
are similar in age, (ib) if A and B
are sufficiently unsimilar in age,
then they have no fossil species in
common, and (iia) the more A and B are
similar in age, the more they are
similar in their FSAs #dat-met

g.title: n178
g.text: LP - CFA ORS - 1
Given the Lyellian Principle and some
ORS strata, it holds: The strata
support a FSA intermediate in
character between those of SIL strata
and ML strata #cha

g.title: n179
g.text: LP - CFA ORS - 2
Given the Lyellian Principle, and some
strata supporting a FSA intermediate
in character between those of SIL
strata and ML strata, then these
strata are ORS in age #cha

g.title: n57
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Assemblage
Principle - V2
Given a sufficiently large (i) amount
of fossils and (ii) region under
study, it holds: There is a bijection
between the age of some strata and its
characteristic fossil species
assemblages #dat-met

g.title: n170
g.text: CFAP and CFA - 2
Given a certain definition of CFA and
the CFA Principle, it holds: For each
time intervall dt, there is at least
one CFA #dat-met

g.title: n196
g.text: Scottland - CFAP - 1
If strata can be identified by means of
their CFAs and the FA characteristic
of the ORS period encompasses only a
few peculiar fish fossils, then
Scottish ORS strata support such a FA
#cor

g.title: n36
g.text: LV in Fauna and Flora
For every time intervall, there are
local variations in the fauna and
flora #dat-met

g.title: n59
g.text: LV in Fauna and Flora - ORS
There are local variations in the fauna
and flora during the ORS period
#dat-met

g.title: n168
g.text: CFs - LV in Fauna and Flora
If there are always local variations in
fauna and flora and some fossil
species f is characteristic for some
time interval dt iff, during dt, every
region supports f,then there are no
characteristic fossils #dat-met

g.title: n171
g.text: LV in Fauna and Flora and CFAs
If there are always local variations in
fauna and flora and some assemblage of
fossil species AS is characteristic
for some time interval dt iff, during
dt, every region supports AS, then
there are no characteristic fossil
species assemblages #dat-met

g.title: n37
g.text: Characteristic Fossil
A fossil species f is characteristic
for some time interval dt iff (i) f
only exisits during dt and (ii) during
dt, every region supports f #dat-met

g.title: n166
g.text: CFP and CF - 1
Given a certain definition of CF, it
holds: If, for each time intervall dt,
there is at least one CF, then there
is a bijection between the age of some
strata and its CFs #dat-met

g.title: n175
g.text: CFs - LV in Fauna and Flora - ORS
If there are local variations in fauna
and flora and some fossil species f is
characteristic for some time interval
dt iff, during dt, every region
supports f,then, during ORS, there is
no characteristic fossils species
#dat-met

g.title: n176
g.text: CFAs - LV in Fauna and Flora - ORS
If there are local variations in fauna
and flora and some fossil species
assemblage FA is characteristic for
some time interval dt iff, during dt,
every region supports FA,then, during
ORS, there is no characteristic FA
#dat-met

g.title: n39
g.text: Characteristic Fossil - Every Time
For each time intervall dt, there is
(at least) one characteristic fossil
species #dat-met

g.title: n42
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Assemblage
An assemblage of fossil species AS is
characteristic for some time interval
dt iff (i) AS only exisits during dt
and (ii) during dt, every region
supports AS #dat-met

g.title: n169
g.text: CFAP and CFA - 1
Given a certain definition of CFA, it
holds: If, for each time intervall dt,
there is at least one CFA, then there
is a bijection between the age of some
strata and its CFAs #dat-met

g.title: n43
g.text: No Characteristic Fossil Assemblage
For every time intervall dt, there is
not one CFA #dat-met

g.title: n44
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Assemblage -
Every Time
For each time intervall dt, there is
(at least) one CFA #dat-met

g.title: n45
g.text: Characteristic Fossil Asseblage - Some
Time
For some time intervall dt, there is
(at least) one characteristic
assemblage of fossil species #dat-met

g.title: n48
g.text: LV in Sedimentation - CM
During the CM period, there are local
variations in sedimentation #dat-met

g.title: n49
g.text: LV in Sedimentation

g.title: n174
g.text: CRTs - LV in Sedimentation
If there are always local variations in
rock types, and some rock type r is
characteristic for some time interval
dt iff, during dt, every region
supports r, then there are no
characteristic characteristic rock
types #dat-met

g.title: n50
g.text: Characteristic Rock Type
A rock type r is characteristic for
some time interval dt iff (i) r have
been formated only during dt and (ii)
during dt, in every region, r have
been formated #dat-met

g.title: n172
g.text: CRTP and CRT - 1
Given a certain definition of CRT, it
holds: If, for each time intervall dt,
there is at least one CRT, then there
is a bijection between the age of some
strata and its CRTs #dat-met

g.title: n177
g.text: CRTs - LV in Sedimentation - ORS
If there are local variations in
sedimentation and some rock type is
characteristic for some time interval
dt iff, during dt, every region
supports f,then, during ORS, there is
no characteristic rock type #dat-met

g.title: n53

ORS intermediate in age between SIL

intermediate in age between SIL and ML
#cha
